To enable secure retrieval of secrets, the Nautilus DevOps team needs to configure access to a secret in AWS Secrets Manager using IAM roles and policies. 
The objective is to allow EC2 instances to retrieve secrets securely. Please complete the following tasks:

1. Create a secret in AWS Secrets Manager named datacenter-app-secret with the following secret string:

	-> {"db_user":"admin","db_pass":"supersecret"}

2. Create an IAM role named datacenter-app-role with EC2 as the trusted entity.

3. Attach an inline IAM policy named datacenter-app-policy that grants permission to retrieve the secret from AWS Secrets Manager.

4. Use the main.tf file (do not create a separate .tf file) to provision the IAM Role and IAM Policy.

5. Create the variables.tf file, ensure the following variables are defined in variables.tf file:

	-> KKE_SECRET_NAME for the secret name.
	-> KKE_SECRET_VALUE for the secret value.
	-> KKE_ROLE_NAME for the IAM role name.
	-> KKE_POLICY_NAME for the IAM policy name.

6. Create the outputs.tf file, and use the following:

	-> KKE_secret_name: The secret name
	-> KKE_role_name: The IAM role name
	-> KKE_policy_name: The IAM policy name
	
	
	
	
Soln:-

Step 1:- Navigate to your Terraform working directory

cd /home/bob/terraform



Step 2:- Verify the provider.tf file with the following content:

terraform {
  required_providers {
    aws = {
      source = "hashicorp/aws"
      version = "5.91.0"
    }
  }
}

provider "aws" {
  region                      = "us-east-1"
  skip_credentials_validation = true
  skip_requesting_account_id  = true
  s3_use_path_style = true

endpoints {
    ec2            = "http://aws:4566"
    apigateway     = "http://aws:4566"
    cloudformation = "http://aws:4566"
    cloudwatch     = "http://aws:4566"
    dynamodb       = "http://aws:4566"
    es             = "http://aws:4566"
    firehose       = "http://aws:4566"
    iam            = "http://aws:4566"
    kinesis        = "http://aws:4566"
    lambda         = "http://aws:4566"
    route53        = "http://aws:4566"
    redshift       = "http://aws:4566"
    s3             = "http://aws:4566"
    secretsmanager = "http://aws:4566"
    ses            = "http://aws:4566"
    sns            = "http://aws:4566"
    sqs            = "http://aws:4566"
    ssm            = "http://aws:4566"
    stepfunctions  = "http://aws:4566"
    sts            = "http://aws:4566"
    rds            = "http://aws:4566"
  }
}



Step 3: Create the "main.tf" file

# Create the secret in AWS Secrets Manager
resource "aws_secretsmanager_secret" "datacenter_secret" {
  name = var.KKE_SECRET_NAME
}

resource "aws_secretsmanager_secret_version" "datacenter_secret_value" {
  secret_id     = aws_secretsmanager_secret.datacenter_secret.id
  secret_string = var.KKE_SECRET_VALUE
}

# Create IAM Role for EC2
resource "aws_iam_role" "datacenter_role" {
  name = var.KKE_ROLE_NAME

  assume_role_policy = jsonencode({
    Version = "2012-10-17"
    Statement = [
      {
        Action    = "sts:AssumeRole"
        Effect    = "Allow"
        Principal = {
          Service = "ec2.amazonaws.com"
        }
      }
    ]
  })
}

# Attach inline IAM policy to allow secret retrieval
resource "aws_iam_role_policy" "datacenter_policy" {
  name = var.KKE_POLICY_NAME
  role = aws_iam_role.datacenter_role.id

  policy = jsonencode({
    Version = "2012-10-17"
    Statement = [
      {
        Action   = [
          "secretsmanager:GetSecretValue"
        ]
        Effect   = "Allow"
        Resource = aws_secretsmanager_secret.datacenter_secret.arn
      }
    ]
  })
}



Step 4: Create the "variables.tf" file

variable "KKE_SECRET_NAME" {
  description = "The name of the secret in AWS Secrets Manager"
  type        = string
}

variable "KKE_SECRET_VALUE" {
  description = "The secret string value stored in AWS Secrets Manager"
  type        = string
}

variable "KKE_ROLE_NAME" {
  description = "The IAM role name for EC2 instances"
  type        = string
}

variable "KKE_POLICY_NAME" {
  description = "The IAM policy name attached to the role"
  type        = string
}



Step 5: Create the "terraform.tfvars" file

KKE_SECRET_NAME  = "datacenter-app-secret"
KKE_SECRET_VALUE = "{\"db_user\":\"admin\",\"db_pass\":\"supersecret\"}"
KKE_ROLE_NAME    = "datacenter-app-role"
KKE_POLICY_NAME  = "datacenter-app-policy"



Step 6: Create the "outputs.tf" file

output "KKE_secret_name" {
  description = "The secret name"
  value       = aws_secretsmanager_secret.datacenter_secret.name
}

output "KKE_role_name" {
  description = "The IAM role name"
  value       = aws_iam_role.datacenter_role.name
}

output "KKE_policy_name" {
  description = "The IAM policy name"
  value       = aws_iam_role_policy.datacenter_policy.name
}



Step 7: Initialize Terraform in the directory
	
terraform init



Step 8: Check the Terraform Directory for the correct syntax

terraform validate



Step 9:- Plan the configuration in the directory

terraform plan



Step 10:- Apply the configuration to create the resources

terraform apply --auto-approve
